Business Problem Understanding

¶

As a data scientist, it is important to understand the business problem in order to develop a successful solution. In this case, the business problem is to reduce traffic in the city by implementing a bike sharing system. To do this, our data science team must identify the metrics that will have a significant impact on bike sharing. This includes the day of the week, the time of year, and the weather.

Once these metrics have been identified, our team can then use machine learning and deep learning algorithms to develop a model that can make predictions about future bike sharing usage. This model can then be used to improve service management and optimize the bike sharing system.

In addition, I must also recommand to consider the environmental impact of the bike sharing system. This includes understanding the impact of bike sharing on air pollution and the local environment.

By understanding the business problem and the potential implications of the bike sharing system, I as data science team-lead will try to develop a successful solution that can reduce traffic in the city and improve the local community. By utilizing machine learning and deep learning algorithms, we will develop a model that can make predictions about future bike sharing usage and optimize the bike sharing system.

Dataset address:

https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/hmavrodiev/london-bike-sharing-dataset

Dataset Feild Description

¶

Field Name Description Unit/Format
timestamp Date andTime Text
cnt Number of shared bikes Number
t1 Real temperature Celsius
t2 Feeling temperature Celsius
hum Humidity Percentage (%)
wind_speed Wind Speed KM/H
weather_code Weather Category Number
is_holiday 1 holiday / 0 non holiday Boolean
is_weekend 1 if the day is weekend Boolean
season 0:Spring; 1:Summer; 2:Fall; 3:Winter Number
weathe_code Description
1 Clear / Sunny
2 Scattered clouds / Few clouds
3 Broken clouds
4 Cloudy
7 Rainy
10 Thunderstorm
26 Snowfall

Pandas as NumPy(pd) are powerful data analysis and manipulation library for Python.

Math library is used to perform basic mathematical operations such as addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division.

Matplotlib and Seaborn are a plotting library for Python. It is used to create 2D graphics, including charts, histograms...

RobustScaler is used to scale numerical data by removing the median and scaling the data according to the quantile range.

XGBRegressor is an XGBoost regressor model from sklearn. It is used to create and evaluate regression models using the XGBoost library.

Mean_absolute_error is a metric from sklearn. It is used to evaluate how close predictions are to their actual values.

Mean_squared_error is a metric from sklearn. It is used to evaluate the difference between predicted and actual values.

Tqdm is a library for displaying progress bars in Python. It is used to visualize the progress of a task, such as a training process or an optimization loop.

Keras (Sequential) is a model from Keras. It is used to create deep learning models, by stacking layers of neural networks together.

Dense is a layer from Keras. It is used to create fully connected layers in a neural network.

Dropout is a layer from Keras. It is used to prevent overfitting in neural networks, by randomly dropping neurons and their connections during training.

LSTM is a layer from Keras. It is used to create a recurrent neural network, which is capable of learning long-term dependencies.

Bidirectional is a layer from Keras. It is used to create a bidirectional recurrent neural network, which can process information in both directions.

In [18]:
q1 = df["cnt"].quantile(0.25)
q3 = df["cnt"].quantile(0.75)
iqr = q3 - q1
df = df[(df["cnt"] >= q1 - 1.5 * iqr) & (df["cnt"] <= q3 + 1.5 * iqr)]
df.shape
Out[18]:
(16739, 13)

This code is calculating the interquartile range (IQR) for the "cnt" column in a dataframe, df. The IQR is calculated by first finding the 25th and 75th percentile values (q1 and q3). The IQR is then calculated by subtracting q1 from q3. Any values that fall outside of 1.5 times the IQR are removed from the dataframe, df, before computing its shape.

In [19]:
print("Number of removed outlier records:", df_backup.shape[0] - df.shape[0])

6. Splitting Data

¶

In [25]:
x = df.drop(["cnt"], axis=1)
y = df["cnt"]
In [26]:
def df_split(df, train_percent):
    split_index = int(train_percent * len(df))
    train = df.iloc[:split_index]
    test = df.iloc[split_index:]
    return train, test
In [27]:
x_train, x_test = df_split(x, 0.7)
y_train, y_test = df_split(y, 0.7)

Above block code is used to split our dataset into a training and testing set based on a specified percentage which we have chosen 70%. The code first calculates the split index, which is the index of the last row that should be included in the training set. It then assigns the rows up to the split index to the training set and the remaining rows to the test set. It then returns the two sets.

8. LSTM (RNN)

¶

We'll be using the Keras library to implement this model.

Spliting Data

In [36]:
training_data_len = math.ceil(len(df) * 0.9)
testing_data_len = len(df) - training_data_len

time_steps = 24
train, test = (
    df.iloc[0:training_data_len],
    df.iloc[(training_data_len - time_steps) : len(df)],
)

print(df.shape, train.shape, test.shape)

(16739, 13) (15066, 13) (1697, 13)

The usual splitting dataset through sklearn library is not working here because the dataset is a time series. This means that the data is dependent on the previous values and thus a regular train/test split would result in data leakage. This would lead to overfitting of the model and inaccurate results. Therefore, a different approach is necessary to make sure that the data is properly split and there is no data leakage.

The total length of the dataset is determined by the length of the dataframe (df). We then calculate the training data length as 90% of the total length of the dataset. The remaining 10% of the data is used for testing. The time_steps value is set to 24. Finally, the training and testing datasets are created by taking the respective 90% and 10% of the data from the dataframe.

In [37]:
train_trans = train[
    ["t1", "t2", "hum", "wind_speed", "is_holiday", "is_weekend"]
].to_numpy()
test_trans = test[
    ["t1", "t2", "hum", "wind_speed", "is_holiday", "is_weekend"]
].to_numpy()

scaler = RobustScaler()
train.loc[
    :, ["t1", "t2", "hum", "wind_speed", "is_holiday", "is_weekend"]
] = scaler.fit_transform(train_trans)
test.loc[
    :, ["t1", "t2", "hum", "wind_speed", "is_holiday", "is_weekend"]
] = scaler.fit_transform(test_trans)

train["cnt"] = scaler.fit_transform(train[["cnt"]])
test["cnt"] = scaler.fit_transform(test[["cnt"]])

In [41]:
model = Sequential()
model.add(Bidirectional(LSTM(50, input_shape=(x_train.shape[1], x_train.shape[2]))))
model.add(Dropout(0.2))
model.add(Dense(units=1))

model.compile(optimizer="adam", loss="mean_squared_error")

The given code is used to create a Bidirectional Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) model. The first line creates a Sequential model which is used to create a linear stack of layers. The next line adds a Bidirectional LSTM layer to the model, with the input shape being set to the shape of the x_train array. The Dropout layer is then added with a dropout rate of 0.2. Finally, a single Dense layer is added to the model. The model is then compiled with the Adam optimizer and mean squared error loss functions.

Dropout is a regularization technique used to reduce overfitting in neural networks. It randomly sets a fraction of input units to 0 at each update during training time, which helps prevent overfitting by reducing the number of parameters that can be updated.

Dense is a layer type in a neural network that is fully connected to all the neurons in the previous layer.

The 50 in LSTM(50) indicates the number of hidden units in the layer. This number is usually chosen based on the size of the dataset and the complexity of the problem.

plt.ylabel("MSE Score")
Out[48]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'MSE Score')

Above block code is used to plot the loss and validation loss scores of the LSTM model over the number of epochs. The values of the loss and val_loss are obtained from the history object of the model. The x-axis is set to the number of epochs and the y-axis is set to the mse score.

The loss is the measure of the difference between the predicted and actual values on the training dataset. It is used to evaluate the model during training. The val_loss is the measure of the difference between the predicted and actual values on the validation dataset. It is used to evaluate the model after each epoch.

If the loss and val_loss scores of the LSTM model are approximately the same after a certain number of epochs, it indicates that the model has converged and is no longer improving. This means that the model has achieved the best possible performance on the given data.

9. Conclusion

¶

The London Bike Sharing dataset was analyzed using various data preprocessing techniques, machine learning algorithms, and deep learning algorithms. The data preprocessing techniques used included removing outliers and normalizing the data. The machine learning algorithms used included XGBoost and the deep learning algorithm used was Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM). The results of the analysis showed that the LSTM algorithm performed better than the XGBoost algorithm, but was more time consuming.

The reseon of choosing these two algorithms is that they are two of the most popular and powerful machine learning and deep learning algorithms. XGBoost is a powerful algorithm for regression and classification tasks, and is well-suited for tabular data. LSTM is a powerful deep learning algorithm for sequence prediction tasks, and is well-suited for time series data. Both algorithms are highly accurate and reliable, and have been used successfully in a variety of applications.

Overall, the analysis of the London Bike Sharing dataset showed that the LSTM algorithm was more accurate and reliable than the XGBoost algorithm. However, the LSTM algorithm was more time consuming and therefore may not be suitable for applications that require real-time predictions. To improve the accuracy and efficiency of the model, further research could be done to optimize the hyperparameters of the LSTM algorithm and to explore other deep learning algorithms such as convolutional neural networks. Additionally, further research could be done to explore the use of ensemble methods to combine the predictions of multiple algorithms for improved accuracy.
